LongDescription: Light cruisers operate as a bridge between capital ships and lighter classes, often equipped with drives and armor fitting for hunting down warships lighter than its weight-class, much like the Vauxhall-class.
FlavorText:
Vauxhalls came around as a runner-up during the competition bid that gave the Alliance the Sprinter. Initially, the Naval Office resisted it but when the Admiralty saw the value in the Vauxhall, I was immediately set to work on manufacturing the warship. It's nothing like the Sprinter-class, more expensive to construct, but its modernized systems have earned it some pretty dedicated followers, or so I hear.

Vauxhall-class Light Cruisers are about as modern as they come. These serve as hunter-killers, made for slipping into asteroid fields or gas clouds to single out warships of a lighter class while also more than capable of taking the fight to heavier warships. As expected, the threat a Vauxhall can pose to a flotilla of, say, frigates is incredibly dangerous, especially as the warship is marginally faster than its intended prey.

Overall, this is a warship that I am pleased to manufacture and study, though I understand the Alliance engineers tend to have a lukewarm view towards the warship's complex drive housing. I do not share this sentiment, obviously.

- F. Autumns, CEO, Falke-Tethys Drive Yards
